message.content: This is a case of a 62-year-old male with a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia who presented with rectal bleeding and abdominal pain. Colonoscopy revealed a mass in the sigmoid colon, which was confirmed to be adenocarcinoma on biopsy. Family history was negative for colon cancer. The patient underwent surgery and is currently receiving chemotherapy.

The patient is a 55-year-old male with a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia. He presents with complaints of abdominal pain, constipation, and rectal bleeding. Colonoscopy reveals a large mass in the sigmoid colon, and biopsy confirms adenocarcinoma. Family history is negative for colon cancer.

The patient is a 55-year-old male with a past medical history significant for hypertension. He presents with symptoms of abdominal pain, bloating, and changes in bowel habits. Family history is negative for colon cancer. Colonoscopy reveals a mass in the sigmoid colon, and biopsy confirms adenocarcinoma.

Mrs. Smith is a 62-year-old female with a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia. She presents with symptoms of abdominal pain and rectal bleeding. Colonoscopy revealed a large mass in the descending colon, and biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma. Family history is positive for colorectal cancer in her mother and sister.
